This leads to a two tiered calculus which has formulas and structures, with structures generalising contexts and being built from structural connectives. 

We briefly comment on the particular choice of structural connectives above.
Keeping with the aim of modularity, D.EAK was designed in such a way that one can drop the exchange rule for `;' and treat non-commutative conjunction and disjunction. This means that we need two adjoints of `;' denoted by $>$ and $<$.

\footnote{

For example, taking into account the correspondence between operational and structural connectives, the rule $(;,>)$ above says precisely that the operation that maps $C$ to $A\rightarrow C$ is right-adjoint to the operation that maps $B$ to $A\wedge B$. Similarly, $(>,:)$ expresses that  $A{\mbox{$\,{\rotatebox[origin=c]{-90}{\raisebox{0.12ex}{${\wedge}$}}{\mkern-2mu{\rule[0.5865ex]{1.38ex}{0.1ex}}}}\,$}} \_$ is left adjoint to $A\vee\_$.

} 

Following the symmetries inherent in this substructural analysis of logic suggests to add the operational connectives ${\mbox{\rotatebox[origin=c]{180}{$\,{\rotatebox[origin=c]{-90}{\raisebox{0.12ex}{${\wedge}$}}{\mkern-2mu{\rule[0.5865ex]{1.38ex}{0.1ex}}}}\,$}}}$, $\leftarrow$, ${\mbox{$\,{\rotatebox[origin=c]{-90}{\raisebox{0.12ex}{${\wedge}$}}{\mkern-2mu{\rule[0.5865ex]{1.38ex}{0.1ex}}}}\,$}}$, but they are not needed in the following. Similarly, the modal operators $[\alpha]$ and $[{\texttt{a}}]$ have structural counterparts $\{\alpha\}$ and $\{{\texttt{a}}\}$ which in turn have adjoints ${\,\rotatebox[origin=c]{90}{$\{\rotatebox[origin=c]{-90}{$\alpha$}\}$}\,}$ and ${\,\rotatebox[origin=c]{90}{$\{\rotatebox[origin=c]{-90}{${\texttt{a}}$}\}$}\,}$. 
The formulas \eqref{eq:fma} do not have operational connectives corresponding to the structural connectives ${\,\rotatebox[origin=c]{90}{$\{\rotatebox[origin=c]{-90}{$\alpha$}\}$}\,}$ and ${\,\rotatebox[origin=c]{90}{$\{\rotatebox[origin=c]{-90}{$\aga$}\}$}\,}$, but they can be added and are indeed useful (in terms of Kripke semantics, the adjoint of a box modality $\Box$ for a relation $R$ is the diamond modality for the converse relation $R^{-1}$ often denoted by $\blacklozenge$).

